Cell["\<\
Much like our result in 3.10 a, this picture is that of a 3d sinusoid that \
oscillates forever. Then, unlike our results in 3.9, this picture seems to \
imply that there are other, simpler solutions to Poisson\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
equation than what we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve previous observed and modeled.   \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.858726186731554*^9, 3.85872622962848*^9}, {
  3.8587262681519203`*^9, 
  3.8587263448542337`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ccf2b092-6ff1-4fac-8d05-\
d6ccbca6d391"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
3.) Discuss how the solutions are modified when applying a Robin boundary \
condition. How does it affect your coefficients? How does it affect the \
overall solution form?\
\>", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.858262874491596*^9, 
  3.85826292747853*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"672ad6ad-53cc-48b2-b922-\
e599c3ccd4d6"],

Cell["\<\
Aside from having to do addition, more difficult, work, applying Robin \
conditions forces us to solve the equations using other methods. For example, \
problem b forces us to solve for the coefficients using a systems of \
equations and to then plug those values back into the series solution. The \
coefficients also seem to be more complex than what we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve \
previously solved for since the initial conditions seem to dictate that \
behavior. As for the final solution form, we tend to get other, more unique, \
solutions to the partial differential equations, as evident from the \
solutions in 3.9 and 3.10. However, it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s worth noting that \
all of the solutions above behave using some form of \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]wave\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] (that\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
a rather broad word) behavior independent of time. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.858720155789238*^9, 3.858720230530882*^9}, {
  3.858720280035056*^9, 3.8587202851741*^9}, {3.858726392348329*^9, 
  3.858726641231955*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0d6c89da-3383-44e7-ae94-\
9b5865c2ec65"]
}, Open  ]],

